  "response": "As of October 2023, the status of Crimea remains internationally disputed. Here's a breakdown:\n\n1. **Russian Control**: In March 2014, Russia annexed Crimea following a controversial referendum. Since then, Crimea has been under de facto Russian control, and Russia treats it as part of its territory.\n\n2. **International Recognition**: The majority of the international community, including the United Nations General Assembly, does not recognize Russia's annexation of Crimea. Most countries consider Crimea to be part of Ukraine.\n\n3. **Ukrainian Position**: Ukraine maintains that Crimea is an integral part of its territory and rejects the annexation as illegal.\n\nIn summary, while Russia controls Crimea and administers it as part of its territory, its status remains contested internationally, and Ukraine continues to assert its claim over the region. The situation is part of the broader geopolitical conflict between Russia and Ukraine, which escalated further with Russia's full-scale invasion of Ukraine in February 2022.",
